[3] Bhutan - free range birds
Date: Sat, 28 Jan 2012
Source: Kuenseonline (Bhutan) [edited]
http://www.kuenselonline.com/2011/?p=25909

Free range birds presage spread of H5N1
-----------------------------------------------------
Poultry farmers in Trashigang who rear poultry birds would rather have their non-egg-laying chickens freed into the farms than have them confined within their coops or culled for meat.

Elsewhere in the world, once a hen’s egg-laying ability ceases after 12 months of laying, they are slaughtered and used in processed foods or for soup.

With the recent case of bird flu in the country [see item 4], the free range chickens in the villages of Trashigang are being seen as posing risk of infecting rest of the birds with the flu.

Trashigang livestock officials and those of the veterinary hospital said that by coming in contact with wild birds, the risk of [H5N1] spreading in the villages was grave.

Home to third largest poultry population in the country it has many chickens both local and improved breed left out in the open to stray.

Farmer Jigme Wangchuk from Tapting under Samkhar gewog has been leaving his local breed of chicken to loiter along the peripheries of the village.

Almost every household in Tapting keep 2 to 3 chickens and they are all left to stray throughout the day. “We free the birds in the villages, especially when everyone’s out in the fields working and have no one to feed the birds,” Jigme Wangchuk said.

A poultry farm owner in the village, Tshering Wangdi scowls at his neighbours who have set their poultry birds free to mingle wild birds like crows and pigeons [see item 5].

"Many of these birds flock in the dozens into the village from various parts of the country," Tshering Wangdi said.

While Tapting has only a handful of local breed birds let loose in the open, villages like Benshingmo in Kanglung have in the hundreds.

Opposed to the idea of culling spent up birds for religious reasons and sentiments, commercial poultry farms in the village have used the community as a dumping ground.

"I gave around 150 spent up birds to a villager from Younphupam for free," poultry farm owner in Drakmawoong Ngawang Dorji said. "I’m opposed to the disposal strategy of culling."

Ngawang Dorji said he gave away between 10 and 15 spent up birds to several villagers.

"I still have 400 layers," he said. "I’m planning them give away to the villages in the next one and half years."

The trend has spread among poultry farm owners in other gewogs [geographic administrative units composed of a group of villages] of Trashigang, where they have been giving away birds to villagers for free or setting them free as tshethar ["saving lives of animal", a cultural compassionate trend in Bhutan].

Although some villagers, who took the birds given to them for free have built a poultry shed, many are rearing in free range.

Dzongkhag veterinary officials said the risk of bird flu outbreak and spreading from the wild birds to the poultry increased manifold if non-laying chickens were left to stray open in the villages.

“Raising birds in free range at such times is risky and poses danger to humans as well,” officiating livestock officer Tandin Gyeltshen said.

Free range poultry were also exposed to outbreak of bird flu from people and vehicle movements in the villages. Veterinary officials said the movement of people in the villages could also transmit the flu if someone coming from an affected area visited the place.

“Bird flu is a viral disease that can be transmitted even by humans,” Tandin Gyeltshen said. “So any unprotected contact with birds can cause an outbreak.”

It is also reported that even in town areas including Melphey and Keyling where people and vehicle movements have been increasing in recent times, people have been rearing free range birds.

Meanwhile, some villagers in Younphupam are believed to be rearing poultry birds at the basement of their houses.

This Trashigang medical officer, Dr Kalpana Chhetri said was unhealthy, unhygienic and risky for both humans and birds.

“Certain safe distance should be maintained,” Dr Kalpana Chhetri said. “Living with birds in the same house would cause acute respiratory infection and aggravate chronic asthma if someone is suffering from it.”

Except of recent sensitisation program on bird flu, little bio-security measures have been taken up.

“We’ve yet to put up to agriculture ministry about the bio-security measures just in case of a bird flu outbreak,” dzongda Lungten Dorji said. “So far, nothing has been done.”

Meantime, veterinary officials said it would explore more precautionary measures to confine the free range birds.

[Byline: Tempa Wangdi]

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>

[A candid description of a situation which will contribute some insight into the difficulties of HPAI control in Asia. -Mod. AS].

